00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:33.650
an empire that began in Anatolia and spread
out to include much of Mesopotamia. In fact,

00:02:33.650 --> 00:02:38.099
they may have even gone to war with the Mycenaean
Greeks in a pre-Homeric Trojan War. How do

00:02:38.099 --> 00:02:40.639
we know this? Well again, Archaeologists.

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:44.180
And this brings up another feature of the
ancient Near East in the late Bronze Age:

00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:49.200
Warfare. There is a fair amount of it between
Egyptian and Hittites and Assyrians and many

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:54.470
other empires which rose and fell over many
hundreds of years. Wars were pretty common

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:59.360
in the period of 1500 to 1200 BCE. You know,
rulers wanted to extended their power and

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:04.010
prestige through military success and conquest.
And also that military success and conquest

00:03:04.010 --> 00:03:08.470
was one of the main drivers of economic growth.
"Eh, we could increase agricultural yields,

00:03:08.470 --> 00:03:13.700
we could come up with more efficient mechanization,
or we could go to war." They always went to war.

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:16.739
But there wasn't just war. There was also
quite a bit of diplomacy. And when diplomats

00:03:16.739 --> 00:03:20.540
from these rival communities would talk to
each other, they would often call each other

00:03:20.540 --> 00:03:25.690
by family names or imagine family relationships,
even though they weren't actually family.

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:29.190
But that sense that they felt like family.
You know, families do sometimes have wars,

00:03:29.190 --> 00:03:34.110
indicates that it wasn't necessarily different
civilizations. And sometimes the wars ended

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:38.599
with diplomatic marriages, so rather than
just pretending that they were family, rulers

00:03:38.599 --> 00:03:43.330
of the late Bronze Age states would actually
become family. And then they could stop fighting

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:48.250
and start trading, at least for a little while.
By the way, this is also the history of Post-Roman

00:03:48.250 --> 00:03:53.190
Empire Europe. So we have a trade network,
we have a lot of interconnected familial relationships

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:57.200
(both real and imagined), but do we have a
civilization? Well, I would argue "yes," even

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:02.140
though it didn't have a single ruler, or one
form of political structure, or even one language.

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:06.299
But neither does "Western" civilization and
lots of people think that's a thing.

00:04:06.299 --> 00:04:10.080
When you think about it, what people often
mean when we talk about civilizations today

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:13.989
are systems. Like when we talk about Western
civilization, we're not actually talking about

00:04:13.989 --> 00:04:19.499
Greece or Rome or England or France or the
United States, we're talking about a set of

00:04:19.499 --> 00:04:24.469
structures, and religious and cultural traditions
that are closely related enough that we see

00:04:24.469 --> 00:04:28.109
them as forming a coherent whole. And the
